-- Taiwan 2018 Bond Yield Drops to Five-Week Low on Stock Selloff
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2013-04-16T02:31:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-16/taiwan-2018-bond-yield-drops-to-five-week-low-on-stock-selloff.html
Taiwan ’s government bonds rose,
with the yield on the 2018 notes dropping to the lowest level in
more than five weeks, as investors cut stock holdings on signs
 China ’s economic growth is losing momentum.  Gross domestic product in China, Taiwan’s biggest export
market, increased 7.7 percent in the first quarter, slowing from
7.9 percent in the previous three months, the National Bureau of
Statistics reported yesterday. That compares with the 8 percent
median estimate in a Bloomberg News survey of 41 economists.
Global funds sold $137 million more Taiwanese shares than they
bought yesterday, taking net sales this month to $294 million,
according to exchange data.  “Optimism about global growth recovery is receding,” said
Sam Chang, a fixed-income trader at Yuanta Securities Co. in
Taipei. “Investors are looking for more evidence and signs
that’ll support a further rally.”  The yield on the 0.875 percent bonds due January 2018
dropped two basis points, or 0.02 percentage point, to 0.942
percent as of 10:16 a.m. in Taipei, according to Gretai
Securities Market. That’s the lowest level since March 7.  Taiwan’s Taiex Index of equities dropped 0.5 percent to
7,721.12, taking losses in the last three days to 1.7 percent.
It touched 7,688.62 earlier, the lowest level since Jan. 28.  The  Taiwan dollar  was little changed at NT$29.933 against
its U.S. counterpart, compared with NT$29.927 yesterday, Taipei
Forex Inc. prices show. The central bank has sold the local
dollar in the run-up to the close on most days in the past year,
according to traders who asked not to be identified.  One-month non-deliverable forwards retreated 0.1 percent to
NT$29.924, data compiled by Bloomberg show. The contracts
touched NT$30.10 on April 9, the lowest level since July 27.
One-month implied volatility, a gauge of expected moves in the
 exchange rate  used to price options, rose six basis points to
3.56 percent.  The  overnight interbank lending  rate was little changed at
0.388 percent, according to a weighted average compiled by the
Taiwan Interbank Money Center.  To contact the reporter on this story:
